    "summary": "Eannatum was a ruler of the Sumerian city-state of Lagash, reigning around 2500–2400 BC, who became one of the first historically documented military conquerors. He unified much of Sumer under Lagash's control, subduing rival cities including Umma, Uruk, Ur, and Akshak, and his victories are commemorated on the [[event:1732|Stele of the Vultures]], one of the earliest narrative monuments in history. The stele depicts his army marching over the bodies of defeated enemies, making it a crucial document for understanding Early Dynastic Mesopotamian warfare.\n\nEannatum's campaigns against the neighboring city of Umma were particularly significant, as the two cities had long disputed control of a fertile agricultural region known as the Gu'edena. The conflict between Lagash and Umma recurred across generations and represents one of the earliest documented territorial disputes in human history. Eannatum's assertion of dominance over much of Sumer was relatively short-lived; the hegemony he established did not long survive him. Nevertheless, his reign provides historians with invaluable early evidence of organized interstate warfare, treaty-making, and political geography in Bronze Age Mesopotamia.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eannatum",
